Wash and dry all produce. Trim, peel, and cut @carrot{3%ounce} into a small dice. Halve, peel, and finely chop @yellow onion{1}. Dice @roma tomato{1}.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{2%teaspoon} in a large #pot{} over medium-high heat. Add @Italian chicken sausage mix{9%ounce} and cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned, ~{4-6%minutes} (it'll finish cooking in the next step).

Add another drizzle of olive oil to pot with sausage, then stir in carrot, onion, and a large pinch of @salt{}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until veggies are just softened and sausage is cooked through, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Add tomato, half the @Italian seasoning{1%tablespoon} (use the rest as you like), and @garlic powder{1/4%teaspoon} (1/2 tsp for 4 servings; you'll use more later) to pot. Cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{1%minute}. Stir in @chicken stock concentrate{2} and 3 1/2 cups warm @water{3 1/2%cups} (6 cups for 4), scraping up any browned bits from bottom of pot. Add half the @farfalle pasta{6%ounce} (all for 4). Cover and bring to a boil, then immediately reduce heat to low. Simmer until pasta is al dente, ~{10%minutes}.

Meanwhile, place @butter{2%tablespoon} (3 TBSP for 4 servings) in a small #microwave-safe bowl{}; microwave until just softened, ~{10%seconds} (do not melt). Stir in @Parmesan cheese{1/4%cup} (2 TBSP for 4; you'll use the rest later), @garlic powder{1/4%teaspoon} (use remaining garlic powder for 4), and a pinch of @salt{} and @chili flakes{1%teaspoon} to taste. Halve @ciabatta bread{1} and toast until golden. Spread butter mixture onto cut sides of ciabatta, then halve on a diagonal.

Stir @spinach{5%ounce} and 2 TBSP Parmesan (4 TBSP for 4 servings) into soup until spinach is wilted. Season with plenty of salt and @pepper{}. Divide soup between bowls; sprinkle with remaining Parmesan and a pinch of chili flakes if desired. Serve with toasts on the side for dipping.

> This is chicken noodle soup the way your Italian grandma would've made it - soul-soothing and with old-world charm.